Exercise 2

Question 1 Normal-Gamma Model

Part A Marginal of location parameter

\[\theta|w \sim N(\mu,(kw)^{-1})\] \[w \sim Ga(\frac{d}{2},\frac{\eta}{2})\] Thus, \[p(\theta,w)=p(\theta|w)p(w)\propto w^{\frac{d+1}{2}-1}e^{-w\frac{k(\theta-\mu)^2}{2}}e^{-w\frac{\eta}{2}}\] The marginal distribution of \(\theta\): \[\begin{align} p(\theta) &= \int p(\theta,w) dw\\ &\propto \int w^{\frac{d+1}{2}-1}e^{-w(\frac{k(\theta-\mu)^2}{2}+\frac{\eta}{2})} dw \\ &\propto \frac{\Gamma(\frac{d+1}{2})}{(\frac{k(\theta-\mu)^2}{2}+\frac{\eta}{2})^{-\frac{d+1}{2}}}\\ &\propto (k(\theta-\mu)^2+\eta)^{-\frac{d+1}{2}}\\ &\propto (1+\frac{1}{d}\frac{(\theta-\mu)^2}{\eta/dk})^{-\frac{d+1}{2}} \end{align}\]

t distribution with \(v=d\), \(m=\mu\), \(s^2=\frac{\eta}{dk}\).

Part B Joint posterior

\[\begin{align} p(\theta,w|y) & \propto p(\theta,w) p(y|\theta,w)\\ &\propto w^{\frac{d+1}{2}-1}e^{-w\frac{k(\theta-\mu)^2}{2}}e^{-w\frac{\eta}{2}} * \prod_i^n \frac{\sqrt{w}}{\sqrt{2\pi}}e^{-\frac{w}{2}(y_i-\theta)^2}\\ & \text{use $\sum(y_i-\theta)^2= S_y+n(\bar(y)-\theta)^2$} \\ & \propto w^{\frac{d+n+1}{2}-1}e^{-\frac{k(\theta-\mu)^2+(S_y+n(\bar{y}-\theta)^2)+\eta}{2}w} \\ & \propto w^{\frac{d+n+1}{2}}e^{-\frac{(k+n)\theta^2-2(k\mu+n\bar{y})\theta+k\mu^2+n\bar{y}^2+S_k+\eta}{2}w} \\ & \propto w^{\frac{d+n+1}{2}-1}e^{-\frac{(k+n)[(\theta-\frac{k\mu+n\bar{y}}{k+n})^2-(\frac{k\mu+n\bar{y}}{k+n})^2]+k\mu^2+n\bar{y}^2+S_k+\eta}{2}w} \\ & \propto w^{\frac{d+n+1}{2}-1}e^{-\frac{(k+n)(\theta-\frac{k\mu+n\bar{y}}{k+n})^2-\frac{(k\mu+n\bar{y})^2}{k+n})+k\mu^2+n\bar{y}^2+S_k+\eta}{2}w} \\ & \propto w^{\frac{d+n+1}{2}-1}e^{-\frac{(k+n)(\theta-\frac{k\mu+n\bar{y}}{k+n})^2-\frac{(k\mu+n\bar{y})^2}{k+n})+k\mu^2+n\bar{y}^2+S_k+\eta}{2}w} \\ & \propto w^{\frac{d+n+1}{2}-1}e^{-\frac{(k+n)(\theta-\frac{k\mu+n\bar{y}}{k+n})^2+\eta+S_k+\frac{kn(\mu-\bar{y})^2}{k+n}}{2}w} \\ \end{align}\]

Thus it is conjugate to the prior as in \[d^*=d+n\] \[k^*=k+n\] \[\mu^*=\frac{k\mu+n\bar{y}}{k+n}\] \[\eta^*=\eta+S_k+\frac{kn(\mu-\bar{y})^2}{k+n}\]

Part C Conditional Posterior

From \[ p(\theta,w|y) \propto w^{\frac{d+n+1}{2}}e^{-\frac{(k+n)(\theta-\frac{k\mu+n\bar{y}}{k+n})^2+\eta+S_k+\frac{kn(\mu-\bar{y})^2}{k+n}}{2}w} \] we can directly see \[p(\theta|y,w) \sim N(\frac{k\mu+n\bar{y}}{k+n},\frac{1}{(k+n)w})\]

Part D Marginal Posterior for scale parameter

Use the notation of \(d^*\), \(n^*\), \(k^*\) in joint posterior in Part B: \[\begin{align} p(w|y) &\propto \int w^{\frac{d^*+1}{2}-1}e^{-\frac{k^*(\theta-\mu^*)^2+\eta^*}{2}w} d\theta\\ & \propto w^{\frac{d^*+1}{2}-1} e^{-\frac{\eta^*}{2}w}\int e^{-\frac{k^*(\theta-\mu^*)^2}{2}w} d\theta \\ & \propto w^{\frac{d^*+1}{2}-1} e^{-\frac{\eta^*}{2}w} \frac{1}{\sqrt{k^*w}}\\ & \propto w^{\frac{d^*}{2}-1} e^{-\frac{n^*}{2}w}\\ & \sim Ga(\frac{d^*}{2},\frac{n^*}{2}) \end{align}\]

Part E Marginal Posterior of location Parameter

\[\begin{align} p(\theta|y) &\propto \int w^{\frac{d^*+1}{2}-1}e^{-\frac{k^*(\theta-\mu^*)^2+\eta^*}{2}w} dw\\ & \text{this is the same as in Part A }\\ & \text{Simply replace $d$ to $d^*$, $\eta$ to $\eta^*$, $k$to $k^*$ and $\mu$ to $\mu^*$ in Part A} \\ & \propto (1+\frac{1}{d^*}\frac{(\theta-\mu^*)^2}{\eta^*/(d^*k^*)})^{-\frac{d^*+1}{2}} \end{align}\]

Part F Non-informative Prior

False. With \(d\), \(n\) and \(k\) going to \(0\), the integral in the density of \(\theta\) and \(w\) would go to infinity, both the \(p(\theta)\) and \(p(w)\) are invalid. Since Gamma distribution requires shape \(>0\), rate \(>0\) and t distribution requires postitive parameters for degrees of freedom \(df\) as well.
Reason: in a gamma \(w^{d-1}e^{-\eta w}\) if \(d\), \(n\) and \(k\) going to \(0\) this would go to \(w^{-1}\), the integral of this \(\int w^{-1} dt=\log(w)|^{\infty}_{0}\) is infinite. And in a \(t\) distribution density kernal \((1+\frac{1}{d}\frac{(\theta-\mu)^2}{\eta/dk})^{-\frac{d+1}{2}}\) will goes to either \((1+0)^{-0.5}=1\) (if \(\eta\) grows faster than \(k\)), meaning \(\int_0^\infty 1 dt=\infty\) or \((1+\infty)^{-\frac{d+1}{2}}=0\) (if \(d\) goes to 0,\(\eta\) grows slower than \(k\)), still meaning invalid integral.

Part G Non-informative Prior

True. \(d\), \(n\) and \(k\) going to \(0\) simply means that \(d^*\), \(k^*\) going to \(n\) and \(\eta^*\) going to \(S_k\), the density of \(p(\theta|y)\) t distribution\(t(\mu=bar{y},v=n,s^2=\frac{S_y}{n^2})\) and \(p(w|y)\) with Gamma \(Ga(\frac{n}{2},\frac{S_k}{2})\) are still valid with proper integral.

Part F Bayesian CI under Non-informative Prior

True. When \(d\), \(n\) and \(k\) goes to \(0\), the bayesian posterior parameter would only depend on data (likelihood) and does not depend on prior. Thus the estimate and the CI would behave the same as Frequenist. As we showed, \(d\), \(n\) and \(k\) going to \(0\) simply means that \(d^*\), \(k^*\) going to \(n\) and \(\eta^*\) going to \(S_k\), \(\mu^*\) going to \(\bar{y}\). \[p(\theta|y)\propto (1+\frac{(\theta-\bar{y})^2}{S_k/n^2}\frac{1}{n})^{-\frac{n+1}{2}} \] The credible interval is \[[\bar{y}-t_{n,\frac{\alpha}{2}}\frac{\sqrt{\sum(y_i-\bar{y})^2}}{n},\bar{y}+t_{n,\frac{\alpha}{2}}\frac{\sqrt{\sum(y_i-\bar{y})^2}}{n}]\] which is the same as the frequenist approach. (Slight difference lies in the degree of freedom in classic approach is \(n-1\) and the \(S_k\) are divided by \(n-1\) instead of \(n\))
In the frequenist approach, we have the sampling distribution of \[\frac{y-\bar{y}}{\frac{\sqrt{\frac{\sum(y_i-\bar{y})}{n-1}}}{\sqrt{n}}}\sim t_{n-1}\] Thus, the frequenist confidence interval is \[[\bar{y}-t_{n-1,\frac{\alpha}{2}}\frac{\sqrt{\sum(y_i-\bar{y})^2}}{\sqrt{n-1}\sqrt{n}},\bar{y}+t_{n-1,\frac{\alpha}{2}}\frac{\sqrt{\sum(y_i-\bar{y})^2}}{\sqrt{n-1}\sqrt{n}}]\] ## Question 2

Part A Conditional posterior for \(\beta\)

\[\beta|w \sim N(m,(wK)^{-1})\] \[w \sim Ga(\frac{d}{2},\frac{n}{2})\]

The joint posterior is: \[\begin{align} p(\beta,w|y) &\propto p(y|\beta,w) p(\beta|w)p(w)\\ &\propto det(2\pi(w\Lambda)^{-1})^{-\frac{1}{2}}e^{-\frac{1}{2}(y-X\beta)^Tw\Lambda(y-X\beta)}det(2\pi(wK)^{-1})^{-\frac{1}{2}}e^{-\frac{1}{2}(\beta-m)^T(wK)(\beta-m)} w^{\frac{d}{2}-1}e^{-\frac{\eta}{2}w} \\ &\propto w^{\frac{d+n+p}{2}-1}e^{-\frac{\eta}{2}w}e^{-\frac{w}{2}(y-X\beta)^T\Lambda(y-X\beta)+(\beta-m)^TK(\beta-m)} \end{align}\] conditional on \(w\), the posterior for \(\beta\) is \[\begin{align} P(\beta|w,y) &\propto p(\beta,w|y)\\ &\propto e^{-\frac{1}{2}(y-X\beta)^Tw\Lambda(y-X\beta)}e^{-\frac{1}{2}(\beta-m)^T(wK)(\beta-m)}\\ &\propto e^{-\frac{1}{2}[(y-X\beta)^Tw\Lambda(y-X\beta)+(\beta-m)^T(wK)(\beta-m)}]\\ &\propto e^{-\frac{1}{2}(\beta^Tw(X^T\Lambda X+K)\beta-2\beta^T w(X^T\Lambda y+Km))} \\ &\text{Note $(Q-A)^TB(Q-A) \propto QBQ-2Q^TBA$}\\ & \sim N(((X^T\Lambda X+K))^{-1}(X^T\Lambda y+Km), (w(X^T\Lambda X+K))^{-1}) \end{align}\]

Part B Marginal posterior for \(w\)

\[\begin{align*} p(w|y) &= \int p(\beta,w|y) d\beta\\ & \propto \int w^{\frac{d+n+p}{2}-1}e^{-\frac{\eta}{2}w}e^{-\frac{w}{2}(y-X\beta)^T\Lambda(y-X\beta)+(\beta-m)^TK(\beta-m)} d\beta \\ & \propto \int w^{\frac{d+n+p}{2}-1}e^{-\frac{\eta}{2}w} e^{-\frac{w}{2}\beta^T(X^T\Lambda X+K)\beta-2\beta^T(X^T\Lambda y + Km)+y^T\Lambda y+ m^T K m} d\beta \\ & \propto \int w^{\frac{d+n+p}{2}-1}e^{-\frac{\eta}{2}w} e^{-\frac{w}{2}[(\beta-\mu)^T\Sigma^{-1}(\beta-\mu)-((X^T \Lambda y +Km)^T(X^T \Lambda X+K)^{-1}(X^T \Lambda y +Km))+y^T\Lambda y+ m^T K m]} d\beta \\ & \text{where $\mu=((X^T\Lambda X+K))^{-1}(X^T\Lambda y+Km)$,$\Sigma=(w(X^T\Lambda X+K))^{-1}$}\\ & \propto w^{\frac{d+n+p}{2}-1}e^{-\frac{\eta}{2}w} e^{-\frac{w}{2}[y^T\Lambda y+ m^T K m-((X^T \Lambda y +Km)^T(X^T \Lambda X+K)^{-1}(X^T \Lambda y +Km))]} \\ & \quad det(2\pi (w(X^T\Lambda X+K))^{-1})^{1/2}\\ & \propto w^{\frac{d+n}{2}-1}e^{-\frac{\eta}{2}w} e^{-\frac{w}{2}[y^T\Lambda y+ m^T K m-((X^T \Lambda y +Km)^T(X^T \Lambda X+K)^{-1}(X^T \Lambda y +Km))]}\\ & \sim Ga(\frac{d+n}{2}, \frac{1}{2}(\eta+ y^T\Lambda y+ m^T K m-((X^T \Lambda y +Km)^T(X^T \Lambda X+K)^{-1}(X^T \Lambda y +Km)))) \end{align*}\]

Part C Margianl Posterior of \(\beta\)

\[\begin{align} p(\beta|y) &= \int p(\beta,w|y) dw\\ & \propto \int w^{\frac{d+n+p}{2}-1}e^{-\frac{\eta}{2}w}e^{-\frac{w}{2}(y-X\beta)^T\Lambda(y-X\beta)+(\beta-m)^TK(\beta-m)} dw \\ &\propto \frac{\Gamma(\frac{d+n+p}{2})}{\frac{( \eta+(y-X\beta)^T\Lambda(y-X\beta)+(\beta-m)^TK(\beta-m))}{2}^{\frac{n+d+p}{2}}} \\ & \propto ( \eta+(y-X\beta)^T\Lambda(y-X\beta)+(\beta-m)^TK(\beta-m))^{-\frac{n+d+p}{2}} \\ & \propto (\eta+ y^T\Lambda y+ m^T K m-((X^T \Lambda y +Km)^T(X^T \Lambda X+K)^{-1}(X^T \Lambda y +Km))+\\ & (\beta-\mu)^T\Sigma^{-1}(\beta-\mu))^{-\frac{n+d+p}{2}} \\ & \text{where $\mu=((X^T\Lambda X+K))^{-1}(X^T\Lambda y+Km)$}\\ & \propto (1+\frac{1}{n+d}\frac{(\beta-\mu)^T(n+d)(w(X^T\Lambda X+K))(\beta-\mu))}{c})^{-\frac{n+d+p}{2}}\\ & \text{where $c=\eta+ y^T\Lambda y+ m^T K m-((X^T \Lambda y +Km)^T(X^T \Lambda X+K)^{-1}(X^T \Lambda y +Km)$} \end{align}\]

Thus, it is a \(t\) distribution of degree of freedom \(n+d\), location \(\mu=((X^T\Lambda X+K))^{-1}(X^T\Lambda y+Km)\), scale \(S^{-1}=\frac{n+d}{\eta+ y^T\Lambda y+ m^T K m-((X^T \Lambda y +Km)^T(X^T \Lambda X+K)^{-1}(X^T \Lambda y +Km)}(w(X^T\Lambda X+K))\). Here the notation of t distribution parameters are generally defined as in \(\propto (1+\frac{1}{df}(\beta-\mu)^TS^{-1}(\beta-\mu))^{\frac{df+p}{2}}\).

Part (D) Fit a Bayesian Linear Regression Model

rm(list=ls())
library(MASS)
library(mvtnorm)
library(matrixStats)
set.seed(111)
setwd("/Users/qiaohui.lin/Desktop/StatModeling2/")
data=read.csv("gdpgrowth.csv",header = TRUE,sep=',')
y=data$GR6096
x=data$DEF60
x_reg= cbind(rep(1,length(x)),x)

#Question 2
iter=3000
n=length(y)
p=2

#initializing the parameters
d=10
eta=1
Lambda=diag(n)
K=diag(c(0.001,0.001))
m=c(0,0)
h=1

### calculate theoretical posterior mean 
beta_post_mean=solve(t(x_reg)%*%Lambda%*%x_reg+K) %*% (t(x_reg)%*% Lambda %*% y + K%*% m)
w_post_mean= ((d+n)/2+p)/((eta+t(y)%*%Lambda%*%y+t(m)%*%K%*%m- -t((t(x_reg)%*% Lambda %*% y + K%*% m)) %*% solve((t(x_reg)%*%Lambda%*%x_reg+K)) %*% (t(x_reg)%*% Lambda %*% y + K%*% m))/2)


#sample posterior beta and plot them
betapos=rmvt(n = 1000, df = n+d ,delta = solve(t(x_reg)%*%Lambda%*%x_reg+K) %*% (t(x_reg)%*% Lambda %*% y + K%*% m), sigma = solve((t(x_reg)%*%Lambda%*%x_reg+K)) /(n+d) * (eta+t(y)%*%Lambda%*%y+t(m)%*%K%*%m- -t((t(x_reg)%*% Lambda %*% y + K%*% m)) %*% solve((t(x_reg)%*%Lambda%*%x_reg+K)) %*% (t(x_reg)%*% Lambda %*% y + K%*% m))[1][1],
             type='shifted')
colMeans(betapos)
## [1] 0.01149047 0.19803110
par(mfrow=c(1,2))
hist(betapos[,1],main='Posterior Intercept',xlab='Intercept,mean=0.0161(0.0169)',col='blue')
abline(v=beta_post_mean[1,],col='red')
hist(betapos[,2],main='Posterior Slope',xlab='Slope,mean=0.041(0.0397)',col='blue')
abline(v=beta_post_mean[2,],col='red')

#sample posterior w and plot them
#Note the values may be shifted because of hyperparameter setting of d
par(mfrow=c(1,1))
wpos=rgamma(n=1000, shape = (d+n)/2+p, rate= (eta+t(y)%*%Lambda%*%y+t(m)%*%K%*%m- -t((t(x_reg)%*% Lambda %*% y + K%*% m)) %*% solve((t(x_reg)%*%Lambda%*%x_reg+K)) %*% (t(x_reg)%*% Lambda %*% y + K%*% m))/2)
hist(wpos,main='Posterior w',xlab='w, mean=86.38(86.57)',col='blue')
abline(v=w_post_mean,col='red')

#fit the line with posterior mean
y_pred=x_reg%*%beta_post_mean

par(mfrow=c(1,1))
plot(x,y_pred,type='l',ylim=c(-0.05,0.08),ylab='',col='red',main='Fitted line with Posterior Beta Mean and 75% Credible Interval')
par(new=TRUE)
plot(x,y,ylim=c(-0.05,0.08),ylab='y',pch=20)

The fit is not very good, as the line is pretty flat and not showing much difference of \(y\) when \(x\) changes. Also, the slope is very much affected by one single outlyer. Third, the residuals have large absolute values, meaning the actual \(y\) is far away from predicted \(y\).

Question 3

Part A

\[p(y_i|\beta,w,\lambda_i)=\frac{\sqrt{w\lambda_i}}{\sqrt{2\pi}}e^{-\frac{w\lambda_i}{2}(y_i-x_i\beta)^2}\] \[p(\lambda_i)\propto \lambda_i^{\frac{h}{2}-1}e^{-\frac{h}{2}\lambda_i}\] Thus, \[p(y_i,\lambda_i|\beta,w)= p(y_i|\beta,w,\lambda_i) * p(\lambda_i)\] And marginalizing out \(\lambda\), \[\begin{align} p(y_i|\beta, w) &=\int p(y_i,\lambda_i|\beta,w) d\lambda_i \\ &\propto \int \frac{\sqrt{w\lambda_i}}{\sqrt{2\pi}}e^{-\frac{w\lambda_i}{2}(y_i-x_i\beta)^2}\lambda_i^{\frac{h}{2}-1}e^{-\frac{h}{2}\lambda_i} d\lambda_i \\ &\propto \int \lambda_i^{\frac{h+1}{2}-1}e^{-\frac{h+w(y_i-x_i\beta)^2}{2}\lambda_i} d\lambda_i \\ &\propto \frac{\Gamma(\frac{h+1}{2})}{(\frac{h+w(y_i-x_i\beta)^2}{2})^{\frac{h+1}{2}}} \\ & \propto \frac{1}{(h+w(y_i-x_i\beta)^2)^{\frac{h+1}{2}}} \\ & \propto (1+\frac{w}{h}(y_i-x_i\beta)^2)^{-\frac{h+1}{2}} \end{align}\]

Part B

\[\begin{align} p(\lambda_i|y,\beta,w) & \propto p(y_i|\beta,w,\lambda_i) p(\lambda_i)\\ & \propto \frac{\sqrt{w\lambda_i}}{\sqrt{2\pi}}e^{-\frac{w\lambda_i}{2}(y_i-x_i\beta)^2}\lambda_i^{\frac{h}{2}-1}e^{-\frac{h}{2}\lambda_i} \\ & \propto \lambda_i^{\frac{h+1}{2}-1}e^{-\frac{h+w(y_i-x_i\beta)^2}{2}\lambda_i} \\ & \sim Ga(\frac{h+1}{2},\frac{h+w(y_i-x_i\beta)^2}{2}) \end{align}\]

Part C

\[\begin{align} p(\beta|y,w,\Lambda) &\propto p(\beta|w)p(w)p(y|\beta,w,\Lambda) \\ & \text{see Question 2 Part A} \\ &\sim N(((X^T\Lambda X+K))^{-1}(X^T\Lambda y+Km), (w(X^T\Lambda X+K))^{-1}) \end{align}\] \[\begin{align} p(w|y,\Lambda) &= \int p(\beta|w)p(w)p(y|\beta,w,\Lambda)d\beta \\ &\text{See Question 2 Part B} \\ & \sim Ga(\frac{d+n}{2}+p, \frac{1}{2}(\eta+ y^T\Lambda y+ m^T K m-((X^T \Lambda y +Km)^T(X^T \Lambda X+K)^{-1}(X^T \Lambda y +Km)))) \end{align}\]

\[p(\lambda_i|y,\beta,w) \sim Ga(\frac{h+1}{2},\frac{h+w(y_i-x_i\beta)^2}{2})\]

Part (D) Gibbs Sampler

#creating empty matrix for storage, each column for one iteration later
iter=10000
n=length(y)
p=2
beta=matrix(0,nrow=p,ncol=(iter+1))
lambda=matrix(0,nrow = n ,ncol=(iter+1))
w <- NULL
#initializing parameters with prior 
#prior d=10,eta=1
d=10
eta=1
w[1]=rgamma(1,d/2,eta/2)
#prior h=1, fill in the first column with prior distribution
h=1
lambda[,1]= rgamma(n,h/2,h/2)
Lambda=diag(lambda[,1])
#prior m=0, K=I, fill in the first column with prior distribution
m=c(0,0)
K=diag(c(0.001,0.001))
beta[,1]=mvrnorm(n=1,mu = m, Sigma = solve(w*K))

#Gibbs sampler
for (j in 2:iter){
  #Update beta
  beta_mu= solve(t(x_reg)%*%Lambda%*%x_reg+K) %*% (t(x_reg)%*% Lambda %*% y + K%*% m)
  beta_Sigma=solve(w[j-1]*(t(x_reg)%*%Lambda%*%x_reg+K))
  beta[,j]=mvrnorm(n=1,mu= beta_mu, Sigma = beta_Sigma)
  #Update w
  w[j]=rgamma(1, shape=(n+d)/2, rate=(eta+t(y)%*%Lambda%*%y+t(m)%*%K%*%m-t(beta_mu)%*%beta_Sigma%*%beta_mu)/2 )
  #Update Lambda
  #each lambda_i in jth iteration is gamma with (h/2+1/2,h/2+(y_i-x_ibeta)^2/2)
  lambda[,j]=sapply((y-x_reg %*% beta[,(j-1)])^2,function (x) rgamma(1,(h/2+1/2),(h/2+x/2)))
  Lambda=diag(lambda[,j])
}


#plot the traceplots for parameters update, evidence of good mixing
plot(beta[1,1000:iter],type='l')

plot(beta[2,1000:iter],type='l')

plot(w,type='l')

hist(1/rowMeans(lambda[,500:iter]),col='blue',main='Posterior Mean of 1/lambda_i')

#burn-in first 1000 
beta_post_mean2=rowMeans(beta[,1000:iter])

y_pred_Gibbs2=x_reg%*%beta_post_mean2


#Put Gibbs sampling result to plot
par(mfrow=c(1,1))
plot(x,y,ylim=c(-0.05,0.08),ylab='y',pch=20,main='Fitted Line with Gibbs Sampler Posterior Mean - Fat tail vs Usual tail')
par(new=TRUE)
plot(x,y_pred_Gibbs2,type='l',ylim=c(-0.05,0.08),ylab='y',col='blue')
lines(x,y_pred,type='l',ylim=c(-0.05,0.08),ylab='y',col='red')
legend('topleft',lty=1,c("fat tail",'usual tail'),col=c('blue','red'))

The fitted line is better than in Question 2 as now we consider the fat tail, the gamma error, and the outlyer does not have a huge bad influence on the fit. (Different hyperparameters may change the plot and slope in this case but the result is generally true.)
